{
  "answer": "**The *Manusmṛti* (Laws of Manu), Chapter 5, presents this argument in three consecutive verses (5.38–40).**[^1][^2][^3]\n\nIt first declares that needlessly killing an animal brings retribution matching the number of its hairs:\n\n> As many hairs as the animal has, so many times does the one who kills it for no reason suffer a violent death in future births.[^1]\n\nIt then justifies ritual killing in sacrifices (explicitly stating \"in a sacrifice, killing is not killing\") and the higher rebirths for the slain:\n\n> Animals were created for the sake of sacrifice by the Self-existent One himself; the sacrifice is for the prosperity of this whole world; therefore, **in a sacrifice, killing is not killing**.[^2]  \n> Herbs, animals, trees, beasts, and birds, **which have met their death for the sake of a sacrifice, attain higher states of existence again**.[^3]\n\nThese verses contrast permissible sacrificial killing (benefiting both sacrificer and victim) with needless slaughter (which incurs karmic punishment).\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 5, paragraph p-42b5e1](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-42b5e1).\n\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 5, paragraph p-d81302](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-d81302).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 5, paragraph p-aa01df](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/05/translation/#p-aa01df).",
